  1. Todays temperature has a high of 15 and a low of -10 degree fahrenheit. Find the corresponding degress in celsius and storage it in a (single) vector named cel. Print the variable.

Answer(1)

fahrenheit <- c(15, -10) 
Celcius = ((fahrenheit - 32) * 5 ) / 9 
cel <- c(Celcius)
print(cel) 
## [1]  -9.444444 -23.333333

  1. How many perfect squares are there between 1 and 1001? Storage the answer in a variable named numPerfect and print. You may want to look at ?round.

Answer(3)

x <- c(1:1001)

y <- round(sqrt(x))^2

func <-ifelse(y == x, 1, 0)

numPerfect <- sum(func > 0)
print(numPerfect)
## [1] 31

Cars and mileage

For this part we will use the mpg data set, you can access the data by loading the package ggplot2 into your R session by executing the command library(ggplot2). The mpg data includes information about fuel economy of popular car models for the years 1999 and 2008 as collected by the US Environmental Protection Agency. An answer should include a short paragraph of text for the explanation to a (human) reader, together with appropriate R code, outputs, and graphs.

  1. Create a scatterplot of hwy and cty and describe the relationship. Why are there so few points visible?

Answer(3)

plot(mpg$hwy, mpg$cty)

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy, y = cty, color = model))+
  geom_point()

Looking at the scatterplot showing the relationship between highway and City we can deduce many things. There seems to be a strong, positive, linear relationship between HighWay Mileage and City Mileage. There appears to be 1 to 3 outliers.

I believe so few points are visble because multiple models of cars have the same fuel efficiency.

  1. Are cars in 2008 more fuel efficient than cars in 1999? Use graphs and summary statistics to answer this question.
#ggplot(mpg, aes(x = year, y = hwy, color = year))+
  #geom_point()

#ggplot(mpg, aes(x = year, y = cty, color = year))+
  #geom_point()

YearData <- subset(mpg, year == '1999')
ggplot(YearData, aes(x = hwy, y = model, color = hwy))+
  geom_point()

YearData2 <- subset(mpg, year == '2008')
ggplot(YearData2, aes(x = hwy, y = model, color = hwy))+
  geom_point()

ggplot(YearData, aes(x = hwy, y = model)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_point(data = YearData2, color = "blue")

ggplot(YearData, aes(x = cty, y = model)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_point(data = YearData2, color = "blue")

Comparing highway and city fuel efficiency of two different years is a little complicated. We can see multiple models of the same year logged different fuel efficiencies. This could be due to the how the driver operated his or her vehicle, the type of the terrain the driver was driving on, etc.
